book'; font-size:12pt">.  In 1996 I founded the Ape Alliance, an international coalition of organizations and individ</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">uals working for the conservation and welfare of apes through collaborative action, advocacy, and public awareness campaigns, and I continue to serve as the Chairman of this organization</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">.  From 2001 to 2012, I</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> serve</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> as chief consultant </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">and Envoy </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">to the Gr</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">eat Apes Survival Partnership, a joint initiative led by the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to lift the threat of imminent extinction faced by</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> great apes. </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> Alth</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ough the focus of my work on primates has been apes, several member organisations in the Ape Alliance are concerned with trade in other primates, and I have contributed to reports </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">and publications </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">relevant to this i</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">nquiry (e.g. the International Fund for A</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">nimal Welfare publication, Born to be Wild: Primates are not Pets