#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Poaching:</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">One of th</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">e greatest threats to the</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> survival</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> of many primate species</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> is poachin</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">g, including killing them</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> for bushmeat and capturing live individuals for illegal trade, which results </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">in dramatic losses t</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">o primate</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> populations.  A</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">dult primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, because of their size</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> and arboreal habits</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, are targeted for bushmeat, sometimes consumed locally but often transported to be sold as a “delicacy” in urban areas.</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  Infant primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, however, can be even more enticing t</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">o poachers, who sell them domestically or internationally for use as pets or in the entertainment industry.  Those infants captured alive for sale, either domestically or internationally, can be worth hundreds of dollars in local African</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, Asian or Latin Am</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">erican</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> markets and </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">depending on the species concerned, potentially </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">thousands of dollars abroad.  T</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">o capture an infant primate</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, its mother and other adults and family members, who often attempt to protect their young, are killed first – it is estimated that</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> for every infant captured alive, up to </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ten con-specifics</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> may be killed, their bodies usually ending up in bushmeat markets.  Thus, demands for bus</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">hmeat and live young primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> combine to drive devastating</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> poaching and trafficking of the</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">e species that are</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> also losing habitat and so teeter</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> on the edge of extinction. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Links to Poverty and Climate Change:</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">Underlying this poaching and</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> trafficking of wild primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> is the combination of widespread poverty in expanding</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> human populations in non-human primate ran</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ge stat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es, which leads rural residents to seek income by exploiting natural resources, and an expanding middle-class in urban areas, leading to a growing c</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ommercial demand for live primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> (for pets and entertainment) and for bushmeat.  There is almost no</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> capital expenditure necessary to become involved in a poaching v</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">enture, save acquiring weapons </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">which are often rented, making it essential for the hunter to kill or capture wildlife,</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> including primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, to pay the owner of the gun as </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">well as profit from t</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">he venture</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">.  The lack of adequate enforcement of wildlife laws in addition to the broadcasted public desire for the spoils of poaching have caused this practice to become more widespread and increasingly unsustainable.  Across Africa today, hu</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">nters enter d</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">windling primate</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> habitat, with access to previously impenetrable forests provided by logging and mining roads,</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> to kill and capture primates</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> and other species.  This loss of breeding adults and their offspring is not only catastrophic </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">to the future of the target </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">species, but also for all those species of plants and animals that are ecologi</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">cally dependent upon them</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">– primates are keystone species in</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> tropical forests that are essential to global climate stability.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Global Markets:</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">To </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">stem the tide of primat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es being removed from the wild, the m</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">arkets for s</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">uch live wild animals</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> must be</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> eliminated.  Today, as noted, non-human primat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es are primarily in demand</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, both within and outside of their natural habitat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, for use as pets and for entert</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ainment purposes.  A driving force for this international market is the legality of private ownership and sale of</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> primates in the United Kingdom and other developed countries</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, which is well known throughout the world.  Because icons of popular culture and </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">wealthy individuals keep them as pets</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">, primat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es are perceived as fashionable and constitute a status symbol.  Individuals in developed and developing countries alike want to emulate the upper echelons of society, and so a m</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">arket for primate</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> infants exists.</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  Some</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> captured primat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es are sold locally, primarily to expatriates, but many are also smuggled internationally, particularly to Egypt, </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">the Middle East,</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> Russia</span><span style="font-family:'Century School