oolbook'; font-size:12pt"> a mere commodity</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">.  Such a message, broadcast directly through internet advertisements and indirectly through unn</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">atural depictions of captive primat</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">es for entertainment purposes, contributes to poaching and</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> trafficking of wildlife – something that the UK Government is comm</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">itted to tackle</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">.  In addition, the lega</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">l inequity that allows people in the UK to own and trade primates while people in many primate range states</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> are strictly prohib</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ited from doing so costs UK</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> conservationist</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">s political capital with range-state</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> decision-m</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">akers and local communities – relationships that are essential for the implementation of successful conservation measures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ban is better than Regulation:</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">  In my view, while the guidelines in the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt">Code of Practice for the Welfare of Privately Kept Non-Hum</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt">an Primates</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt">’ do</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">provide aspirational standards for captive care, the reality is that enforcement of these guidelines is inadequate to prevent the suffering of non-human primates being kept as pets.</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">   As long as such high-price animals are allowed to be bred and sold as pets in the UK, individual primates will suffer psychological damage in poor captive conditions and efforts to protect wild primates will be hampered.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">In conclusio</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">n,</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> therefore, I rei</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">terate my statement </span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">in the IFAW publication, Born to be Wild: Primates are not Pets:  </span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To be consistent with the UK’s commitment to conserve global biodiversity, as discussed above, and to assist rather than jeopardise the recovery of wild primate populati</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ons, the buying and selling of primates as pets should be prohibited, and the keeping of them as pets phased out.</span><span style="font-family:Century; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">Submit</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt">ted on</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> 14</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Century Schoolbook'; font-size:12pt"> January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p s